{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1e9a5466-7e02-4d2d-befa-4ddc358dce14","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01YNw9BjkDYUr7Fsr341TcT3","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Explaining .NET 10 migration"},"type":"function"}],"interactionId":"bdb3e682-4c22-48a0-b74c-3e88d8cbc73e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about specific breaking changes and new behaviors when upgrading from .NET 9 to .NET 10. Let me address each point:\n\n1. **InlineArray with explicit StructLayout** - In .NET 10, there's a breaking change where `[InlineArray]` structs no longer allow explicit `[StructLayout]` attributes with `Size` specified. The runtime now computes the size automatically based on the element type and length.\n\n2. **DriveInfo.DriveFormat on Linux** - In .NET 10, `DriveInfo.DriveFormat` on Linux changed from returning the file system type name (like \"ext4\") to returning the mount point or something different. \n\nI'm trying to pin down exactly what changed with `DriveInfo.DriveFormat` on Linux between versions—whether it now throws an exception, returns different values, or changed how it retrieves the file system information from the system. I think the actual issue is that on Linux, `DriveInfo.DriveFormat` now pulls the filesystem type directly from statfs/fstatfs instead of parsing /proc/mounts, so the returned values might be different or use numeric codes rather than the string representations code was expecting.\n\nFor the NU1510 warnings about pruned package references, I can suppress them or disable the feature entirely with `<PrunePackageReferences>false</PrunePackageReferences>` in the project file, or just add the transitive dependencies explicitly. And for the transitive NuGet dependency auditing, .NET 10 changed the default `NuGetAuditMode` to check all dependencies instead of just direct ones.\n\nOn `FilePatternMatch.Stem`, the behavior changed so it never returns null anymore—it returns an empty string instead, which means any null checks will always fail. For the `InlineArray` with `StructLayout` issue, applying explicit layout attributes to inline array structs is now a compile-time error in .NET 10.\n\nFor `DriveInfo.DriveFormat` on Linux, the source of the format string changed, so code doing string comparisons against specific formats needs to be updated. The `NU1510` warning about package pruning happens because .NET 10 enables this by default—you can either add explicit package references for what you need or disable pruning entirely. And for the NuGet audit change, .NET 10 switched to auditing transitive dependencies by default instead of just direct ones.\n\nFinally, `FilePatternMatch.Stem` is no longer nullable and returns an empty string instead of null, so any null checks need to switch to `string.IsNullOrEmpty()`.","outputTokens":1327,"requestId":"A450:20684E:7117A35:79799F8:6A03D105"},"id":"bbfb3029-784c-4721-9700-6e77306b4c9a","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:17:24.601Z","parentId":"b294426d-c746-485f-8b11-d0ea594fe767"}
